1300
01:34:10,481 --> 01:34:13,006
- Private York reporting, sir.
- Have him come in.

1301
01:34:13,084 --> 01:34:15,143
Yes, sir. Go in, Sergeant.

1302
01:34:19,357 --> 01:34:22,918
I'm a-bringing your book back, Major.
And I'm a-thanking you.

1303
01:34:22,994 --> 01:34:24,928
Well, you're welcome, York.

1304
01:34:24,996 --> 01:34:27,658
I done what you told me,
I thought things over.

1305
01:34:27,732 --> 01:34:30,599
- Well?
- I'd like to stay in this here army.

1306
01:34:31,235 --> 01:34:33,100
I rather hoped that you would, York.

1307
01:34:33,171 --> 01:34:36,766
But there's just one thing, sir,
that I ought to tell you.

1308
01:34:37,542 --> 01:34:38,736
There's lots of things...

1309
01:34:38,810 --> 01:34:40,937
There's lots of things
I ain't figured out yet.

1310
01:34:41,012 --> 01:34:43,913
Lots of things still a-going on in my mind.

1311
01:34:44,015 --> 01:34:47,644
But it's...
Well, it's just like Pastor Pile done told me.

1312
01:34:47,919 --> 01:34:52,618
I reckon I can just be a-trusting in
something that's a heap bigger than I be.

1313
01:34:55,059 --> 01:34:59,996
York, as your superior officer, I don't feel
called upon to look into your conscience.

1314
01:35:00,832 --> 01:35:03,357
It's enough for me that I trust you.

1315
01:35:03,835 --> 01:35:07,498
And I believe that when the time comes,
you'll conduct yourself as a soldier should.

1316
01:35:07,572 --> 01:35:08,834
Thank you, sir.

1317
01:35:08,906 --> 01:35:12,740
And I'm going to approve your promotion
to the rank of corporal.

1318
01:35:12,810 --> 01:35:16,610
Well, I'll sure take care of my men
the best I can, sir.

1319
01:35:16,714 --> 01:35:18,545
I know you will, York.

1320
01:35:19,150 --> 01:35:21,345
- That's all.
- Thank you, Major.

1321
01:35:24,822 --> 01:35:28,622
Aren't you...
Aren't you taking quite a chance, Major?

1322
01:35:29,126 --> 01:35:31,993
You mean as to whether he'll fight or not?

1323
01:35:32,830 --> 01:35:35,060
No, I don't think so, Captain.

1324
01:35:35,766 --> 01:35:38,701
I don't think I'm taking any chances at all.

1325
01:35:47,078 --> 01:35:48,409
"Dear Mom,

1326
01:35:48,746 --> 01:35:52,978
"am feeling just fine
and have taken in all the sights.

1327
01:35:53,050 --> 01:35:57,544
"And Bert took me to a church
called Notre Dame Cathedral.

1328
01:35:58,489 --> 01:36:02,949
"It's big enough inside for a fellow
to plant a crop of corn.

1329
01:36:05,296 --> 01:36:07,025
"Pusher just come in.

1330
01:36:07,098 --> 01:36:11,194
"He's saying our outfit is moving up
to front pretty soon.

1331
01:36:11,802 --> 01:36:16,102
"I reckon that's so
'cause we got all our training

1332
01:36:16,173 --> 01:36:20,041
"and they ain't brought us here
for no sight-seeing tour..."

1333
01:36:20,111 --> 01:36:22,102
"Tour, nohow.

1334
01:36:23,414 --> 01:36:26,781
"Gracie wrote in her letter
she was a-worrying.

1335
01:36:27,618 --> 01:36:29,279
"Tell her, don't."

1336
01:36:30,855 --> 01:36:33,881
I was feared. I'm a-feared for Alvin.

1337
01:36:34,659 --> 01:36:37,651
It ain't right for us to be a-feared, Gracie.

1338
01:36:39,030 --> 01:36:40,895
Alvin's in good hands.

1339
01:36:42,300 --> 01:36:45,758
The Lord takes care of 'em
that's a-believing in Him.

1340
01:37:16,267 --> 01:37:19,065
- Any of you blokes got a cigarette?
- Yeah.

1341
01:37:19,370 --> 01:37:21,270
- Here you are.
- Thanks.

1342
01:37:21,505 --> 01:37:24,269
You know, you Yanks just got here
in the nick of time.

1343
01:37:24,342 --> 01:37:26,401
We're running shy of these.

1344
01:37:26,811 --> 01:37:28,836
Besides, we can do with some help.

1345
01:37:28,913 --> 01:37:30,175
Look out.

1346
01:37:37,855 --> 01:37:41,791
It takes a while, but you'll learn
when to flop and when not to.

1347
01:37:42,026 --> 01:37:44,620
They say you never hear
the one that's hit you.

1348
01:37:44,695 --> 01:37:46,856
That's only half the truth.

1349
01:37:46,931 --> 01:37:50,731
No, the whole truth is,
if you hears it, you've got a chance.

1350
01:37:51,702 --> 01:37:52,794
Duck.

1351
01:37:57,274 --> 01:37:58,639
See what I mean?

1352
01:37:58,876 --> 01:38:03,108
- Heinie's got the range good.
- Yeah. A guy can get killed around here.

1353
01:38:03,714 --> 01:38:07,172
- Look out.
- Don't be afraid. This one'll pass over.

1354
01:38:09,353 --> 01:38:10,411
See?

1355
01:38:13,524 --> 01:38:16,687
Takes time, it do.
But you'll get the hang of it.

1356
01:38:17,662 --> 01:38:18,822
Duck again.

1357
01:38:28,139 --> 01:38:31,666
If that was shrapnel, now,
we wouldn't be flopping at all.

1358
01:38:31,742 --> 01:38:34,142
You know, you only flop for...

1359
01:38:35,746 --> 01:38:38,374
Okay, Bert. The Express has gone through.

1360
01:38:38,449 --> 01:38:39,780
Hey, Bert!

1361
01:38:54,832 --> 01:38:58,529
If one's got your name on it,
there's nothing you can do.

1362
01:39:11,682 --> 01:39:15,516
So you see, gentlemen,
the grave responsibility rests upon us.

1363
01:39:16,387 --> 01:39:19,447
This entire German salient,
holding up the Argonne advance

1364
01:39:19,523 --> 01:39:22,583
depends for ammunition and supplies
on the Decauville Railroad,

1365
01:39:22,660 --> 01:39:25,356
which as you know,
lies just beyond these hills.

1366
01:39:25,463 --> 01:39:26,760
It must be taken.

1367
01:39:26,831 --> 01:39:28,264
This is all open country ahead,

1368
01:39:28,332 --> 01:39:31,165
but you can expect heavy machinegun fire
from these wooded ridges

1369
01:39:31,235 --> 01:39:35,137
on the right and the left flanks.
But we've got to get through.

1370
01:39:35,740 --> 01:39:37,708
Synchronize your watches.

1371
01:39:38,943 --> 01:39:41,878
Use as a mark, 4:32.

1372
01:39:42,947 --> 01:39:46,383
It is now minus 10, eight, six,

1373
01:39:46,884 --> 01:39:49,546
four, two, mark.

1374
01:39:49,620 --> 01:39:50,678
Any questions?

1375
01:39:50,755 --> 01:39:52,882
What about artillery support,
Captain Tillman?

1376
01:39:52,957 --> 01:39:55,585
Artillery will lay down a rolling barrage
at 6:00.

1377
01:39:55,659 --> 01:39:57,786
Zero hour will be 6:10.

1378
01:40:02,867 --> 01:40:06,030
I'd like to know where that barrage is
that we're supposed to have.

1379
01:40:06,103 --> 01:40:10,802
Runners, notify the platoon commanders
that we go over, barrage or no barrage.

1380
01:40:10,875 --> 01:40:12,467
First platoon at 6:10,

1381
01:40:12,543 --> 01:40:15,011
second and third platoons to follow
in waves of 100 meters.

1382
01:40:15,079 --> 01:40:16,341
Yes, sir.

1383
01:40:30,194 --> 01:40:32,094
- 6:10.
- 6:10. All right.

1384
01:40:51,882 --> 01:40:53,349
Come on, men!

1385
01:43:08,018 --> 01:43:09,508
Halt and take cover!

1386
01:43:22,433 --> 01:43:23,991
We'll never get through.

1387
01:43:26,136 --> 01:43:27,899
We gotta wipe out those nests.

1388
01:43:27,972 --> 01:43:31,703
Early, take what's left of your section
and work your way back around that hill.

1389
01:43:31,775 --> 01:43:33,402
Maybe you can jump 'em from behind.

1390
01:43:33,477 --> 01:43:37,413
All right. Savage, York, Cutting.
Bring your men. Come with me.

1391
01:44:07,945 --> 01:44:09,276
Take cover.

1392
01:44:11,548 --> 01:44:12,708
Listen.

1393
01:44:34,238 --> 01:44:35,432
Heinie!

1394
01:44:36,607 --> 01:44:37,733
Listen.

1395
01:44:42,112 --> 01:44:43,477
We're not far enough back.

1396
01:44:43,547 --> 01:44:44,571
Savage, keep the men quiet.

1397
01:44:44,648 --> 01:44:46,707
Cutting, come up here with that bayonet.

1398
01:45:12,042 --> 01:45:16,342
We're right behind their lines.
We'll skirt this ridge and flank 'em.

1399
01:45:17,214 --> 01:45:18,704
Look! Heinies!

1400
01:45:19,483 --> 01:45:21,075
Come on, get 'em.

1401
01:45:41,205 --> 01:45:42,365
Hold your fire!

1402
01:45:42,439 --> 01:45:45,931
Fall on down and keep 'em covered.
Spread out, men! Spread out!

1403
01:45:46,643 --> 01:45:48,270
Line 'em up and disarm 'em!

1404
01:45:49,646 --> 01:45:51,273
- Get back there.
- Get 'em up there.

1405
01:45:51,348 --> 01:45:52,576
Go on.

1406
01:46:30,988 --> 01:46:33,286
- I'm hit bad, Cutting.
- Me, too.

1407
01:46:34,224 --> 01:46:35,384
Savage.

1408
01:46:36,360 --> 01:46:37,418
Savage?

1409
01:46:38,028 --> 01:46:39,325
Where's Savage?

1410
01:46:39,730 --> 01:46:42,528
I seen him go down.
They like to cut him in two.

1411
01:46:42,599 --> 01:46:44,760
You're the only noncom left.

1412
01:46:47,104 --> 01:46:49,504
York, take over.

1413
01:46:50,040 --> 01:46:52,736
- Did you hear what I said?
- I heard you.

1414
01:46:54,211 --> 01:46:55,872
Watch this fellow.

1415
01:46:56,680 --> 01:46:59,046
The rest of you keep under cover.

1416
01:47:00,918 --> 01:47:02,442
Come back here.

1417
01:47:02,553 --> 01:47:05,579
- Where are you going?
- You done give me command.

1418
01:47:50,701 --> 01:47:51,998
Hey, Alvin!

1419
01:48:00,310 --> 01:48:02,471
Well, he cleaned out
that machine gun nest.

1420
01:48:29,940 --> 01:48:32,170
Zeekenny, Donahue! The rest of you guys,

1421
01:48:32,242 --> 01:48:34,710
keep your eye on them Heinies
so they don't try any rough stuff.

1422
01:48:34,778 --> 01:48:36,473
Don't try anything funny.

1423
01:48:36,546 --> 01:48:38,514
Belly to the ground, you babies.

1424
01:48:38,582 --> 01:48:39,606
We better get up there.

1425
01:48:39,683 --> 01:48:41,844
No, we better keep an eye
on these prisoners.

1426
01:48:54,031 --> 01:48:57,023
Five will get you 10 that guy knocks off
your whole sauerkraut army.

1427
01:48:57,100 --> 01:48:59,568
There are 25 machine guns on that ridge.

1428
01:48:59,636 --> 01:49:01,968
- Tell him it's useless.
- What did you say?

1429
01:49:02,039 --> 01:49:03,597
I said tell him it's useless.

1430
01:49:03,674 --> 01:49:06,973
You tell him.
You talk better English than I do.

1431
01:49:28,131 --> 01:49:30,326
Just like a flock of turkeys.

1432
01:49:55,125 --> 01:49:58,060
All right. Come on out of there! All of you!

1433
01:49:59,663 --> 01:50:01,153
Come this a-way.

1434
01:50:06,236 --> 01:50:09,569
Tell the rest of them fellows
to quit shooting and come on out of there.

1435
01:50:13,910 --> 01:50:17,437
Keep 'em hands up
and start a-going down the hill there.

1436
01:50:20,484 --> 01:50:21,849
Keep a-coming.

1437
01:50:23,854 --> 01:50:26,516
Go on. Move out of there, down the hill.

1438
01:50:28,725 --> 01:50:30,693
All right. Keep a-coming.

1439
01:50:31,895 --> 01:50:34,386
Hey, down there. Don't do no shooting.

1440
01:50:34,498 --> 01:50:36,022
All right, get on down!

1441
01:50:38,502 --> 01:50:40,766
Come on out and keep your hands up.

1442
01:50:40,837 --> 01:50:42,395
Boy, I told you.

1443
01:50:47,878 --> 01:50:48,936
Look at that mob.

1444
01:50:49,012 --> 01:50:50,673
Hey, we can't handle all that gang.

1445
01:50:50,747 --> 01:50:52,374
Sure we can. That's my mate.

1446
01:50:52,449 --> 01:50:54,713
Come on, step lively. Move forward.

1447
01:50:54,785 --> 01:50:56,150
Get going.

1448
01:50:56,620 --> 01:50:58,713
- Move forward.
- Move it, now.

1449
01:51:00,223 --> 01:51:01,451
Move forward, there.

1450
01:51:01,525 --> 01:51:04,050
Come on, step up. Step lively there.
Come on.

1451
01:51:08,064 --> 01:51:10,430
- All right.
- Get those hands up. Get in there.

1452
01:51:10,500 --> 01:51:12,695
- Come on.
- Come on, get going.

1453
01:51:12,769 --> 01:51:14,100
Nice going, York.

1454
01:51:14,171 --> 01:51:17,265
- Come on there. Come on.
- Come on, get in there.

1455
01:51:17,541 --> 01:51:20,567
Get those hands up.
Come on, move fast. Move.

1456
01:51:20,644 --> 01:51:22,703
- Hiya, Pusher.
- That was a good job, pal.

1457
01:51:22,779 --> 01:51:26,044
- Where's the Sergeant?
- Over there. Hurt pretty bad.

1458
01:51:26,683 --> 01:51:29,447
- How many men we got left?
- Eight, besides you.

1459
01:51:32,556 --> 01:51:33,818
Watch them fellows.

1460
01:51:33,890 --> 01:51:35,858
Get in there, you guys.
Move forward. Move...

1461
01:51:44,000 --> 01:51:45,126
Pusher.

1462
01:51:45,802 --> 01:51:47,030
Pusher.

1463
01:51:47,604 --> 01:51:50,129
This is where we change cars, Alvin.

1464
01:51:52,375 --> 01:51:54,138
The end of the line.

1465
01:52:02,152 --> 01:52:04,814
Who done that?
Who throwed that grenade?

1466
01:52:10,060 --> 01:52:13,154
Come on, you, put your hands up
and keep 'em up.

1467
01:52:14,498 --> 01:52:16,125
You know what I'm a-saying?

1468
01:52:16,199 --> 01:52:17,791
- You understand?
- Yeah.

1469
01:52:17,868 --> 01:52:20,098
Tell 'em men of yours
if any more of that happens

1470
01:52:20,170 --> 01:52:23,401
you and a lot more of 'em's
going to be mighty sorry.

1471
01:52:23,473 --> 01:52:24,701
Go ahead.

1472
01:52:27,377 --> 01:52:29,072
Tell 'em to drop their belts.

1473
01:52:35,685 --> 01:52:37,778
Look them fellows over good.

1474
01:52:41,124 --> 01:52:43,251
- You ready back there?
- Okay here.

1475
01:52:43,326 --> 01:52:45,817
- Okay. Ready here.
- Watch 'em.

1476
01:52:49,733 --> 01:52:51,132
Now, get going.

1477
01:53:07,951 --> 01:53:09,646
Tell 'em to halt.

1478
01:53:12,522 --> 01:53:14,422
If you wanted to get back
to the American lines,

1479
01:53:14,491 --> 01:53:16,789
which way would you be a-going?

1480
01:53:16,860 --> 01:53:18,122
Up there.

1481
01:53:19,062 --> 01:53:21,189
We'll go this a-way. Go on.

1482
01:53:31,841 --> 01:53:33,706
Hey, tell 'em to halt.

1483
01:53:35,845 --> 01:53:36,903
What's up?

1484
01:53:36,980 --> 01:53:39,744
Sounds like them Heinies
is making a heap of trouble.

1485
01:53:41,985 --> 01:53:44,818
- What are we gonna do about it?
- Get 'em.

1486
01:53:45,055 --> 01:53:46,886
We got enough to take care of already.

1487
01:53:46,957 --> 01:53:48,652
And a few more won't make no difference.

1488
01:53:48,725 --> 01:53:49,953
Hey, you.

1489
01:53:50,226 --> 01:53:52,660
Signal up there
and tell 'em they're surrounded.

1490
01:53:52,729 --> 01:53:56,665
Tell 'em to drop their guns
and come down with their hands up.

1491
01:53:58,301 --> 01:54:01,236
Hey, this gun touches off kind of easy.

1492
01:54:49,386 --> 01:54:51,718
They sure are trained good, Major.

1493
01:54:53,823 --> 01:54:55,552
Hey, Sarge, look.

1494
01:54:56,092 --> 01:54:58,253
- Looks like Heinies.
- Stand ready.

1495
01:55:00,330 --> 01:55:01,820
Hello, there!

1496
01:55:01,998 --> 01:55:04,262
- A Yank.
- It may be some kind of a trick.

1497
01:55:04,334 --> 01:55:06,598
- There's something funny here.
- Let 'em get a little closer.

1498
01:55:06,670 --> 01:55:08,604
- Hello there!
- Who are you?

1499
01:55:08,672 --> 01:55:12,039
Detail of the 328th.
We got some prisoners.

1500
01:55:13,043 --> 01:55:15,068
- Halt where you are.
- Halt!

1501
01:55:16,046 --> 01:55:17,479
That's a Yank, all right.

1502
01:55:17,547 --> 01:55:20,744
- Come out, let's have a look at you.
- Watch 'em, fellows!

1503
01:55:26,723 --> 01:55:28,350
Keep 'em covered.

1504
01:55:31,127 --> 01:55:32,458
Where you going?

1505
01:55:32,529 --> 01:55:35,157
Can you tell me where the 328th be?

1506
01:55:35,231 --> 01:55:36,823
It's up that way someplace.

1507
01:55:36,900 --> 01:55:40,358
- Where did you pick up all this bunch?
- Back up the line a ways.

1508
01:55:40,437 --> 01:55:42,667
You couldn't be taking 'em off our hands,
could you?

1509
01:55:42,739 --> 01:55:44,536
What would we do with them?

1510
01:55:44,774 --> 01:55:46,537
Well, I don't rightly know.

1511
01:55:46,609 --> 01:55:48,577
- Can we be going?
- Sure. Go ahead.

1512
01:55:48,645 --> 01:55:49,907
Thank you.

1513
01:55:50,980 --> 01:55:52,004
Come on.

1514
01:55:52,082 --> 01:55:53,310
Forward!

1515
01:56:12,802 --> 01:56:14,133
All right. Halt!

1516
01:56:14,204 --> 01:56:16,001
Prisoners, hold right there!

1517
01:56:17,073 --> 01:56:18,904
Be a-watching 'em, Joe.

1518
01:56:26,282 --> 01:56:28,011
Beg your pardon, sir.

1519
01:56:28,284 --> 01:56:29,342
Yeah?

1520
01:56:29,419 --> 01:56:32,820
We all got some prisoners,
can we be a-leaving 'em here?

1521
01:56:33,490 --> 01:56:35,481
Put 'em right over there.

1522
01:56:36,993 --> 01:56:38,426
Wait a minute.

1523
01:56:39,429 --> 01:56:40,521
How many have you got?

1524
01:56:40,597 --> 01:56:42,997
Well, I done counted 132 heads, sir.

1525
01:56:43,066 --> 01:56:46,229
We haven't room for that many here.
Take them back up the line.

1526
01:56:46,302 --> 01:56:48,395
- Yes, sir, but...
- But what?

1527
01:56:48,571 --> 01:56:52,940
Well, sir, we can't find our outfit and we
tried to drop 'em off two other places.

1528
01:56:53,009 --> 01:56:55,068
And they ain't but only eight of us
to handle them.

1529
01:56:55,145 --> 01:56:59,445
- You should've brought more men.
- But that's all there were of us, sir.

1530
01:57:00,116 --> 01:57:02,983
You mean to say that you
and seven others captured all that bunch?

1531
01:57:03,052 --> 01:57:06,249
Yes, sir.
And we'd kind of like to get rid of 'em.

1532
01:57:06,756 --> 01:57:08,747
Well, good Lord.

1533
01:57:09,692 --> 01:57:11,489
I guess we can give you some help.

1534
01:57:11,561 --> 01:57:13,495
- Come on, Sergeant.
- Thank you.

1535
01:57:20,103 --> 01:57:23,539
Hey, Sarge! York by himself
captured 132 Germans.

1536
01:57:23,606 --> 01:57:27,337
Guy named York got 132 Heinies
all by his Ionesome.

1537
01:57:27,410 --> 01:57:29,605
- How did he do it?
- Must have surrounded him.

1538
01:57:29,679 --> 01:57:32,045
- Guy named York.
- That's what they say.

1539
01:57:32,115 --> 01:57:34,913
Gee, he captured
hundreds of Boche and machine guns.

1540
01:57:34,984 --> 01:57:37,953
Guy named York! All by his Ionesome!

1541
01:57:38,021 --> 01:57:39,818
Hey, what's that? How many?

1542
01:57:39,889 --> 01:57:42,084
A whole division and a lot of high officers.

1543
01:57:42,158 --> 01:57:44,558
- I'm telling you, York?
- Who's they?

1544
01:57:44,627 --> 01:57:46,618
Yeah, about half the German army
and a general.

1545
01:57:46,696 --> 01:57:48,061
- I don't know.
- One guy.

1546
01:57:48,131 --> 01:57:49,359
How could one guy...

1547
01:57:49,432 --> 01:57:51,662
- Guy named York.
- What's that?

1548
01:57:51,734 --> 01:57:54,066
They say he captured Hindenburg.
And the Crown Prince.

1549
01:57:54,137 --> 01:57:56,571
And brought them all back. They say...

1550
01:58:02,712 --> 01:58:05,977
Say, Sarge, did you hear?
York captured the Kaiser.

1551
01:58:09,419 --> 01:58:12,286
Now, as I understand it, York,
your detail came over that ridge there

1552
01:58:12,355 --> 01:58:14,323
and captured about 30 men,
right down in here.

1553
01:58:14,390 --> 01:58:15,414
Yes, sir.

1554
01:58:15,491 --> 01:58:17,322
Then you were forced to cover
by a machine gun

1555
01:58:17,393 --> 01:58:19,554
that was right up on this other ridge.

1556
01:58:19,629 --> 01:58:21,620
Yes, sir. Right up there.

1557
01:58:22,432 --> 01:58:23,558
Where were you?

1558
01:58:23,633 --> 01:58:26,932
Well, I was...
I was a-laying behind that log there.

1559
01:58:27,503 --> 01:58:31,633
They was machine-gunning us
pretty heavy, so I worked my way across

1560
01:58:32,075 --> 01:58:34,805
up behind that log there under the hill.

1561
01:58:36,512 --> 01:58:38,309
Rather incredible, wasn't it, York,

1562
01:58:38,381 --> 01:58:41,282
your being able to cross so much
open ground without being hit?

1563
01:58:41,351 --> 01:58:44,377
I reckon the good Lord
was a-protecting me, sir.

1564
01:58:44,454 --> 01:58:46,479
What did you wanna go over there for?

1565
01:58:46,556 --> 01:58:48,319
Well, I figured that was a good place to be

1566
01:58:48,391 --> 01:58:51,087
because they had to rear up
and show themselves

1567
01:58:51,160 --> 01:58:53,685
in order to shoot at me
and the rest of the boys back here.

1568
01:58:53,763 --> 01:58:55,628
And whenever they did,
I could touch 'em off.

1569
01:58:55,698 --> 01:58:56,722
I see.

1570
01:58:56,799 --> 01:59:00,565
So, I went up the hill,
up around that a-way,

1571
01:59:00,937 --> 01:59:04,634
then worked my way down the ridge
to a place where they was flanked

1572
01:59:04,707 --> 01:59:07,403
and couldn't show themselves
without being hit.

1573
01:59:07,510 --> 01:59:10,070
So, they... Well, they finally gave up.

1574
01:59:10,146 --> 01:59:12,011
How many did you kill?

1575
01:59:13,216 --> 01:59:15,116
I don't rightly know, sir.

1576
01:59:15,184 --> 01:59:17,414
I think Captain Danforth
is familiar with that, sir.

1577
01:59:17,487 --> 01:59:20,923
We counted about 20 bodies altogether
up around there.

1578
01:59:21,925 --> 01:59:24,120
What were your men doing
all this time, Corporal?

1579
01:59:24,193 --> 01:59:25,717
Well, I couldn't just answer that, sir.

1580
01:59:25,795 --> 01:59:28,696
I was pretty busy
and I reckon they was, too.

1581
01:59:28,898 --> 01:59:32,265
According to the statements of the others,
they were guarding the prisoners

1582
01:59:32,335 --> 01:59:35,827
and couldn't expose themselves
to the fire from the ridge.

1583
01:59:35,905 --> 01:59:38,806
All right, gentlemen. That's all, Corporal.

1584
01:59:43,579 --> 01:59:44,841
Corporal.

1585
01:59:46,482 --> 01:59:49,781
- There's something that I'd like to know.
- Yes, sir?

1586
01:59:49,986 --> 01:59:52,648
That night that you reported back to me
at Camp Gordon,

1587
01:59:52,722 --> 01:59:55,987
you as much as told me that you were
quite prepared to die for your country,

1588
01:59:56,059 --> 01:59:57,651
but not to kill.

1589
01:59:58,895 --> 02:00:01,659
What made you
decide to change your mind?

1590
02:00:02,065 --> 02:00:03,498
Well, sir...

1591
02:00:03,599 --> 02:00:06,727
Of course, if you'd rather not tell me,
why, it's quite all right.

1592
02:00:06,803 --> 02:00:09,499
Well, I'm as much against killing as ever,
sir.

1593
02:00:09,639 --> 02:00:11,573
But it was this way, Colonel.

1594
02:00:11,975 --> 02:00:14,671
When I started out I felt just like you said.

1595
02:00:14,744 --> 02:00:16,837
But when I hear them
machine guns a-going

1596
02:00:16,913 --> 02:00:19,404
and all them fellows
are dropping around me,

1597
02:00:19,515 --> 02:00:23,576
I figured that them guns
was killing hundreds, maybe thousands,

1598
02:00:23,653 --> 02:00:26,850
and there weren't nothing anybody
could do, but to stop them guns.

1599
02:00:26,923 --> 02:00:28,788
And that's what I done.

1600
02:00:29,425 --> 02:00:32,053
You mean to tell me
that you did it to save lives?

1601
02:00:32,128 --> 02:00:34,596
Yes, sir. That was why.

1602
02:00:37,500 --> 02:00:42,130
Well, York, what you've just told me
is the most extraordinary thing of all.

1603
02:00:44,507 --> 02:00:45,997
<i>Sergeant</i> York!

1604
02:01:14,670 --> 02:01:16,194
Thank you, sir.

1605
02:01:17,373 --> 02:01:20,433
And for conspicuous gallantry
beyond the call of duty,

1606
02:01:20,510 --> 02:01:23,911
you have been awarded
the Distinguished Service Cross.

1607
02:01:29,185 --> 02:01:32,677
Sergeant York, I am proud that
you are of the All-American Division.

1608
02:01:32,755 --> 02:01:35,622
It's a privilege to command
such men as you.

1609
02:01:39,629 --> 02:01:41,096
Sergeant York,

1610
02:01:41,164 --> 02:01:44,930
as Commander-in-Chief
of the American Expeditionary Forces,

1611
02:01:45,001 --> 02:01:47,629
it is my pleasure to confer upon you

1612
02:01:47,703 --> 02:01:50,194
the United States
Congressional Medal of Honor

1613
02:01:50,273 --> 02:01:52,764
for heroism beyond the call of duty.

1614
02:01:55,011 --> 02:01:56,535
Thank you, sir.

1615
02:02:23,439 --> 02:02:25,236
I'm Cordell Hull, Sergeant York,

1616
02:02:25,308 --> 02:02:27,208
representative from
your district of Tennessee.

1617
02:02:27,276 --> 02:02:29,403
I'm mighty glad to meet you, Mr. Hull.

1618
02:02:29,479 --> 02:02:31,913
And this is Mr. Harrison
from the Tennessee Society.

1619
02:02:31,981 --> 02:02:33,915
Tennessee is indeed proud, Sergeant.

1620
02:02:33,983 --> 02:02:36,008
- Thank you.
- This way, Sergeant.

1621
02:02:47,964 --> 02:02:50,558
Well, Sergeant, what do you think of it?

1622
02:02:50,633 --> 02:02:53,898
Appears like everybody's
having a mighty good time.

1623
02:02:54,170 --> 02:02:56,730
So, Sergeant,
in the name of the people of New York,

1624
02:02:56,806 --> 02:02:59,274
may I present you with this key to our city

1625
02:02:59,342 --> 02:03:01,867
as a token of our very great esteem.

1626
02:03:02,011 --> 02:03:03,876
And may God bless you.

1627
02:03:06,215 --> 02:03:07,477
Thank you for what you said,

1628
02:03:07,550 --> 02:03:10,314
and I'm sure grateful to you
for this here key.

1629
02:03:10,386 --> 02:03:12,877
Well, thank you. And thank you all.

1630
02:03:14,690 --> 02:03:18,126
Now, Sergeant, the people of New York
would like to show their appreciation.

1631
02:03:18,194 --> 02:03:19,957
Is there anything we can do for you?

1632
02:03:20,029 --> 02:03:22,054
Well, there's just one thing
I'd like to ask you.

1633
02:03:22,131 --> 02:03:23,257
And that is?

1634
02:03:23,332 --> 02:03:24,856
Well, if it's all the same to everybody,

1635
02:03:24,934 --> 02:03:28,768
I sure would like to ride on the subway
on the Bronx Express.

1636
02:03:29,238 --> 02:03:30,466
I think we can arrange that.

1637
02:03:34,844 --> 02:03:36,471
Well, here we are.

1638
02:03:41,050 --> 02:03:43,848
I hope you will be comfortable here,
Sergeant York.

1639
02:03:43,920 --> 02:03:45,785
Well, if it ain't, I'd be pretty hard to please.

1640
02:03:45,855 --> 02:03:48,688
If there's anything you require,
all you will have to do is ask for it.

1641
02:03:48,758 --> 02:03:50,658
Thank you. Thank you, sir.

1642
02:03:51,727 --> 02:03:54,719
An awful lot of room
for just one fellow here.

1643
02:04:10,279 --> 02:04:13,180
This here is mighty thoughtful of you,
gentlemen.

1644
02:04:13,249 --> 02:04:16,047
I reckon you know I ain't seen my ma
for quite a spell.

1645
02:04:16,118 --> 02:04:18,245
So we understand.

1646
02:04:24,427 --> 02:04:26,190
Representative Hull.

1647
02:04:27,296 --> 02:04:29,491
Oh, yes, yes. Are they ready?

1648
02:04:30,266 --> 02:04:31,665
Put them on.

1649
02:04:31,901 --> 02:04:34,267
- Somebody for you, Sergeant.
- Me?

1650
02:04:37,506 --> 02:04:38,871
Thank you.

1651
02:04:42,144 --> 02:04:44,203
Hello. Hello there.

1652
02:04:47,416 --> 02:04:48,508
What?

1653
02:04:50,386 --> 02:04:51,717
Who is it?

1654
02:04:54,490 --> 02:04:56,355
I... I can't hear you.

1655
02:04:57,393 --> 02:05:00,021
- Who is it?
- What's that you're saying?

1656
02:05:00,363 --> 02:05:01,694
I can't hear you.

1657
02:05:01,764 --> 02:05:03,732
Put it up to your ear, Mother York.

1658
02:05:03,799 --> 02:05:05,232
Stand closer, Ma.

1659
02:05:05,301 --> 02:05:07,633
When are you coming home, Alvin?

1660
02:05:08,304 --> 02:05:12,035
I said, when are you coming home?

1661
02:05:15,278 --> 02:05:16,939
Oh, I'm glad, Son.

1662
02:05:18,681 --> 02:05:20,171
I'll tell her.

1663
02:05:20,583 --> 02:05:22,244
She's right here.

1664
02:05:23,152 --> 02:05:25,518
He wants to talk to you, Gracie.

1665
02:05:27,490 --> 02:05:30,015
It's me, Alvin. It's me, Gracie!

1666
02:05:30,459 --> 02:05:32,984
We're all in here in Pastor Pile's store.

1667
02:05:33,062 --> 02:05:35,553
He's got this here phone in here now.

1668
02:05:35,631 --> 02:05:38,464
Oh, I just can't wait to see you again,
Alvin.

1669
02:05:38,634 --> 02:05:40,625
I can't wait to see you.

1670
02:05:40,703 --> 02:05:44,002
Yeah, yeah. I'll be coming home, Gracie,
right away.

1671
02:05:44,507 --> 02:05:45,599
Yeah.

1672
02:05:46,442 --> 02:05:49,809
- Goodbye. Goodbye, Gracie.
- Goodbye, Alvin.

1673
02:05:51,347 --> 02:05:52,405
Bye.

1674
02:06:01,023 --> 02:06:03,253
Sure was nice to talk to the folks.

1675
02:06:03,326 --> 02:06:05,726
- I'm a-thanking you.
- You're welcome, Sergeant.

1676
02:06:30,786 --> 02:06:33,721
Just like the electric signs
down the street.

1677
02:06:36,592 --> 02:06:40,426
How do you like New York, Alvin,
as much as you've seen of it?

1678
02:06:41,063 --> 02:06:42,928
- Mr. Hull?
- Yes, Alvin?

1679
02:06:44,033 --> 02:06:46,001
I wanna be a-going home.

1680
02:06:46,535 --> 02:06:48,002
When do you think I can go?

1681
02:06:48,070 --> 02:06:50,903
- You're pretty anxious, I reckon.
- Yes, sir, I am.

1682
02:06:51,774 --> 02:06:53,332
I've got to get to work.

1683
02:06:53,409 --> 02:06:56,742
Well, as far as that goes,
there's plenty to do right here, Alvin.

1684
02:06:56,812 --> 02:06:57,801
What do you mean?

1685
02:06:57,880 --> 02:07:00,280
I've been wanting
to talk to you about this.

1686
02:07:00,349 --> 02:07:02,340
You're a pretty famous man now.

1687
02:07:02,418 --> 02:07:05,046
And judging by all these offers
you've been getting,

1688
02:07:05,121 --> 02:07:07,351
it seems a lot of people realize it.

1689
02:07:07,423 --> 02:07:08,890
For instance,

1690
02:07:09,358 --> 02:07:12,191
two companies want you
in motion pictures,

1691
02:07:12,261 --> 02:07:14,957
ziegfeld wants you in an act
in his new <i>Fo//ies.</i>

1692
02:07:15,030 --> 02:07:18,227
And here's an offer to appear
at the Winter Garden, that's a theater.

1693
02:07:18,300 --> 02:07:22,327
And here's a breakfast food manufacturer
who wants you to endorse his product.

1694
02:07:22,405 --> 02:07:24,168
What does that mean?

1695
02:07:24,874 --> 02:07:29,402
Well, you've to tell him how much
you like it, how much good it's done you.

1696
02:07:30,045 --> 02:07:33,071
I ain't never ate
any of that there breakfast food.

1697
02:07:33,149 --> 02:07:34,946
Doesn't seem to make any difference.

1698
02:07:35,017 --> 02:07:37,508
Anyway, I've totaled the offers so far

1699
02:07:37,586 --> 02:07:40,555
and they amount to around
a quarter of million dollars.

1700
02:07:40,623 --> 02:07:42,682
They're offering me all that money?

1701
02:07:42,758 --> 02:07:45,454
It's just a plain business proposition.

1702
02:07:46,128 --> 02:07:49,256
I sure could do a powerful sight
with that money.

1703
02:07:49,432 --> 02:07:51,923
There was a piece of bottomland
I was a-trying to get...

1704
02:07:52,001 --> 02:07:54,231
Here's your chance to get it.

1705
02:07:56,038 --> 02:07:59,599
Are they offering that money
because of what happened over there?

1706
02:07:59,675 --> 02:08:02,109
- Well...
- That's it, ain't it?

1707
02:08:03,446 --> 02:08:04,777
That's it.

1708
02:08:06,182 --> 02:08:08,707
What... What would you do, Mr. Hull?

1709
02:08:10,386 --> 02:08:12,752
Well, I think that's up to you, Alvin.

1710
02:08:13,122 --> 02:08:14,646
I reckon it is.

1711
02:08:14,824 --> 02:08:17,759
Take all the time you want to think it over.

1712
02:08:18,060 --> 02:08:20,392
I've done thought it over, Mr. Hull.

1713
02:08:20,463 --> 02:08:23,296
I ain't proud of what happened over there.

1714
02:08:23,432 --> 02:08:26,629
What we done in France
was something we had to do.

1715
02:08:26,735 --> 02:08:29,533
Some fellows done it ain't a-coming back.

1716
02:08:30,506 --> 02:08:34,670
So, the way I figure,
things like that ain't for buying and selling.

1717
02:08:34,777 --> 02:08:36,438
So I reckon I'll have to refuse 'em.

1718
02:08:36,512 --> 02:08:39,606
Would you be a-telling them that
for me, please?

1719
02:08:39,782 --> 02:08:42,080
And tell 'em I'm a-going home?

1720
02:08:45,421 --> 02:08:48,948
- I'll be more than glad to, Alvin.
- Thank you, Mr. Hull.

1721
02:08:55,397 --> 02:08:57,922
Here she comes, zeke. Right on time.

1722
02:09:09,678 --> 02:09:11,270
Oh, there he is!

1723
02:09:27,396 --> 02:09:28,590
Alvin!

1724
02:09:28,664 --> 02:09:30,222
Oh, Alvin!

1725
02:09:30,799 --> 02:09:31,993
How are you?

1726
02:09:53,656 --> 02:09:55,123
Ma, I'm back.

1727
02:09:56,125 --> 02:09:58,355
I'm right glad, Son.

1728
02:10:01,430 --> 02:10:03,864
Hey, Alvin. How about your medals?

1729
02:10:04,133 --> 02:10:07,227
- What about 'em, George?
- I thought you'd be wearing 'em.

1730
02:10:07,303 --> 02:10:08,531
You'll be a-seeing 'em.

1731
02:10:08,604 --> 02:10:11,038
They better be a-something big.

1732
02:10:11,273 --> 02:10:12,604
As I was saying, Alvin,

1733
02:10:12,675 --> 02:10:16,111
of course, I always figured
on marrying you and Gracie myself,

1734
02:10:16,178 --> 02:10:19,113
but I ain't one to take the job away
from the Governor of the State.

1735
02:10:19,181 --> 02:10:21,843
Why, you're the dang-swangest hero
raised in these parts

1736
02:10:21,917 --> 02:10:23,680
since Daniel Boone and Andy Jackson.

1737
02:10:23,752 --> 02:10:25,117
Sure are, Alvin.

1738
02:10:25,788 --> 02:10:27,312
Hang on, Rosie.

1739
02:10:29,625 --> 02:10:30,649
Hey,

1740
02:10:31,193 --> 02:10:34,720
what about that there piece of land
I was aiming to get in Tomkins holler?

1741
02:10:34,797 --> 02:10:37,288
- It's still there, I reckon?
- Yep, it's still there.

1742
02:10:37,366 --> 02:10:39,926
Somebody else has got it by now,
I suppose.

1743
02:10:40,002 --> 02:10:44,063
Well, I couldn't rightly expect zeb
to hold it for me all this time.

1744
02:10:44,139 --> 02:10:46,505
I sure would like to see that there
piece of land, though.

1745
02:10:46,575 --> 02:10:48,805
I reckon ain't no harm you seeing it, Alvin.

1746
02:10:48,877 --> 02:10:50,970
I'd like to be a-seeing it, too.

1747
02:10:51,547 --> 02:10:55,005
I'll let you off at the fork and
you and Gracie can walk over to the holler.

1748
02:10:56,418 --> 02:10:58,079
Hang on, everyone.

1749
02:11:01,690 --> 02:11:03,214
Hey, look here.

1750
02:11:05,027 --> 02:11:08,758
- Somebody's done fixed up this old bridge.
- Yeah, they have.

1751
02:11:09,598 --> 02:11:12,032
Gracie, I... I gotta talk to you.

1752
02:11:12,601 --> 02:11:14,466
It wasn't just the land
I was a-wanting to see.

1753
02:11:14,536 --> 02:11:17,198
There's something we got to talk about.

1754
02:11:17,339 --> 02:11:20,502
- Miss Gracie, I'm plumb worried.
- What about, Alvin?

1755
02:11:20,576 --> 02:11:22,441
Well, what with the governor fixing
to marry us

1756
02:11:22,511 --> 02:11:24,206
and all them people coming here
from all over...

1757
02:11:24,279 --> 02:11:27,737
Sure takes a body's breath away,
but I reckon we'll get through it all right.

1758
02:11:27,816 --> 02:11:31,183
- Well, it ain't just that I'm worried about.
- Well, what then?

1759
02:11:31,253 --> 02:11:35,451
Well, it sure looks like I ain't got nothing
to offer you excepting a big wedding.

1760
02:11:35,524 --> 02:11:37,788
Why, some girls don't even get that.

1761
02:11:38,293 --> 02:11:41,387
Well, I reckon you'd like a place to sleep,
wouldn't you?

1762
02:11:41,463 --> 02:11:42,930
Oh, I don't know.

1763
02:11:42,998 --> 02:11:45,262
I done a heap of sleeping
while you was away.

1764
02:11:45,334 --> 02:11:48,394
You sure ain't expecting
too much of a husband.

1765
02:11:48,637 --> 02:11:50,730
I'm expecting my husband to love me.

1766
02:11:50,806 --> 02:11:53,331
I reckon the good Lord
will take care of the rest.

1767
02:11:53,409 --> 02:11:55,900
Well, looks like he's done a heap already,

1768
02:11:55,978 --> 02:11:57,969
just a-having you. But...

1769
02:11:58,213 --> 02:12:01,842
Well, I was expecting to take over
from here myself.

1770
02:12:01,917 --> 02:12:04,511
I reckon you'll get to do your share.

1771
02:12:05,120 --> 02:12:07,884
No, Gracie, it can't be that a-way.

1772
02:12:08,424 --> 02:12:09,413
We got to wait.

1773
02:12:09,491 --> 02:12:12,790
Maybe in another two or three years,
if you're willing to wait...

1774
02:12:12,861 --> 02:12:14,726
Oh, but I ain't, that's the point.

1775
02:12:14,797 --> 02:12:18,426
- You mean you won't wait?
- There ain't no need of waiting.

1776
02:12:18,867 --> 02:12:22,496
Now, Alvin, you keep looking down
and don't you be looking up till I tell you.

1777
02:12:23,505 --> 02:12:24,733
Come on.

1778
02:12:30,713 --> 02:12:32,704
There! Now you can look.

1779
02:12:33,348 --> 02:12:35,680
What do you see, Alvin? Tell me.

1780
02:12:35,951 --> 02:12:38,920
It's yours, Alvin. It's all yours.
They give it to you.

1781
02:12:38,987 --> 02:12:41,820
The people of the state of Tennessee
for what you done.

1782
02:12:41,890 --> 02:12:43,824
- You mean...
- Only, it's 200 acres

1783
02:12:43,892 --> 02:12:47,953
and the house is bigger, with more
windows, and the kitchen's got a pump.

1784
02:12:48,630 --> 02:12:50,222
And it's for us.

1785
02:12:55,804 --> 02:12:58,637
The Lord sure does move
in mysterious ways.

1786
02:12:59,975 --> 02:13:01,203
Come on.

1787
02:14:01,937 --> 02:14:02,926
English


